00:00:02.420 --> 00:00:04.040
- [Narrator] Our solar system is one

00:00:04.050 --> 00:00:06.460
of over 500 known solar systems

00:00:06.460 --> 00:00:08.493
in the entire Milky Way galaxy.

00:00:10.030 --> 00:00:11.810
The solar system came into being

00:00:11.810 --> 00:00:15.290
about 4.5 billion years ago, when a cloud

00:00:15.290 --> 00:00:17.940
of interstellar gas and dust collapsed,

00:00:17.940 --> 00:00:20.940
resulting in a solar
nebula, a swirling disc

00:00:20.940 --> 00:00:24.233
of material that collided
to form the solar system.

00:00:25.890 --> 00:00:27.540
The solar system is located

00:00:27.540 --> 00:00:30.410
in the Milky Way's Orion star cluster.

00:00:30.410 --> 00:00:34.970
Only 15% of stars in the
galaxy host planetary systems,

00:00:34.970 --> 00:00:37.763
and one of those stars is our own sun.

00:00:40.150 --> 00:00:43.420
Revolving around the
sun are eight planets.

00:00:43.420 --> 00:00:45.850
The planets are divided
into two categories,

00:00:45.850 --> 00:00:47.420
based on their composition,

00:00:47.420 --> 00:00:49.610
Terrestrial and Jovian.

00:00:49.610 --> 00:00:52.700
Terrestrial planets including
Mercury, Venus, Earth,

00:00:52.700 --> 00:00:56.170
and Mars, are primarily
made of rocky material.

00:00:56.170 --> 00:00:59.310
Their surfaces are solid,
they don't have ring systems,

00:00:59.310 --> 00:01:01.670
they have very few or no moons,

00:01:01.670 --> 00:01:03.543
and they are relatively small.

00:01:05.740 --> 00:01:08.520
The smallest and closest
to the sun is Mercury,

00:01:08.520 --> 00:01:10.870
which has the shortest
orbit in the solar system

00:01:10.870 --> 00:01:12.623
at about three Earth months.

00:01:13.520 --> 00:01:16.180
Venus is the hottest
planet, with temperatures

00:01:16.180 --> 00:01:20.500
of up to 867 degrees
Fahrenheit, due to an atmosphere

00:01:20.500 --> 00:01:23.970
of carbon dioxide and
extensive lava flows.

00:01:23.970 --> 00:01:28.200
Next to this world of fire
is a world of water, Earth.

00:01:28.200 --> 00:01:30.450
The water systems on
this planet help create

00:01:30.450 --> 00:01:32.560
the only known environment in the universe

00:01:32.560 --> 00:01:34.383
capable of sustaining life.

00:01:36.140 --> 00:01:38.870
The last of the terrestrial planets, Mars,

00:01:38.870 --> 00:01:43.430
might have also supported life
about 3.7 billion years ago,

00:01:43.430 --> 00:01:46.893
when the planet had a watery
surface, and moist atmosphere.

00:01:48.830 --> 00:01:50.470
Beyond the four Terrestrial planets

00:01:50.470 --> 00:01:53.260
of the inner solar system
lie the Jovian planets

00:01:53.260 --> 00:01:55.140
of the outer solar system.

00:01:55.140 --> 00:01:58.890
The Jovian planets include
gas giants Jupiter and Saturn

00:01:58.890 --> 00:02:01.800
and ice giants Uranus and Neptune.

00:02:01.800 --> 00:02:04.290
The gas giants are
predominantly made of helium

00:02:04.290 --> 00:02:08.360
and hydrogen, and the ice
giants also contain rock, ice,

00:02:08.360 --> 00:02:12.100
and a liquid mixture of
water, methane, and ammonia.

00:02:12.100 --> 00:02:14.980
All four Jovian planets
have multiple moons,

00:02:14.980 --> 00:02:19.313
sport ring systems, have no
solid surface, and are immense.

00:02:20.830 --> 00:02:23.300
The largest Jovian is
also the largest planet

00:02:23.300 --> 00:02:25.393
in the solar system, Jupiter.

00:02:26.380 --> 00:02:30.443
Nearby is Saturn, the solar
system's second largest planet.

00:02:31.370 --> 00:02:33.160
Its signature rings are wide enough

00:02:33.160 --> 00:02:35.580
to fit between Earth and the moon,

00:02:35.580 --> 00:02:37.493
but are barely a kilometer thick.

00:02:39.930 --> 00:02:43.530
Past Saturn are the ice
giants, Uranus and Neptune.

00:02:43.530 --> 00:02:46.260
The slightly bigger of
these ice giants, Uranus,

00:02:46.260 --> 00:02:48.443
is famous for rotating on its side.

00:02:50.450 --> 00:02:53.700
Next to Uranus is Neptune,
the outermost planet

00:02:53.700 --> 00:02:57.240
in the solar system, and
also one of the coldest.

00:02:57.240 --> 00:03:00.400
Orbiting the Terrestrial
planets is the asteroid belt,

00:03:00.400 --> 00:03:03.170
a flat disc of rocky
objects, full of remnants

00:03:03.170 --> 00:03:05.120
from the solar system's formation.

00:03:05.120 --> 00:03:07.260
From microscopic dust particles,

00:03:07.260 --> 00:03:11.023
to the largest known object,
the dwarf planet, Ceres.

00:03:12.500 --> 00:03:15.510
Another disc of space debris
lies much further out,

00:03:15.510 --> 00:03:19.193
and orbits the Jovian
planets, the icy Kuiper Belt.

00:03:20.200 --> 00:03:23.040
Apart from asteroids, the
Kuiper Belt is also home

00:03:23.040 --> 00:03:24.840
to dwarf planets, such as Pluto,

00:03:24.840 --> 00:03:27.710
and is the birthplace of many comets.

00:03:27.710 --> 00:03:30.410
Beyond the Kuiper Belt is the Oort Cloud,

00:03:30.410 --> 00:03:33.630
a vast, spherical
collection of icy debris.

00:03:33.630 --> 00:03:36.280
It is considered the
edge of the solar system

00:03:36.280 --> 00:03:38.180
since that is where the gravitational

00:03:38.180 --> 00:03:40.663
and physical influences of the sun end.

00:03:41.720 --> 00:03:44.240
Our solar system's
particular configuration

00:03:44.240 --> 00:03:46.880
of planets and other celestial objects,

00:03:46.880 --> 00:03:49.240
all revolving around a life-giving star,

00:03:49.240 --> 00:03:51.833
make it a special place to call home.


